The breakeven stock prices can be calculated by subtracting the premium received for each option sold from the strike price of that option, then adding this result to the strike price of the corresponding long position (put). For example, the first breakeven calculation would be as follows: 

For the short $42 put with a strike price of $42, subtract the premium of $1.28 from $42: 
($42 - $1.28) + ($42 * 100) = $43.92 per share. 
The second put has a lower strike price of $40, so its break-even price will be higher than the previous one. Subtract the premium of $0.85 from $40: 
($40 - $0.85) + ($40 * 100) = $40.85 per share. 
For the short $47 call, subtract the premium of $0.86 from $47: 
($47 - $0.86) + ($47 * 100) = $47.04 per share. 
For the last long call, we have to calculate the breakeven point separately since there are no available options to compare it against. In order to determine if the trade will make money, we need to consider whether the underlying asset's price will cross above the upper boundary of our bear put spread or below the lower boundary of our bull call spread. If either occurs before expiry, both trades will return a profit; otherwise neither trade will generate a profit.

The second set of calculations will determine the break-even stock price for buying the calls. We use the same method here by subtracting the cost of each option from the strike price of that option. For the $195 call bought at $11.2, the break-even stock price would be:

$195 + $11.2 = $206.20

For the $200 call bought at $8.03, the break-even stock price would be:

$200 + $8.03 = $208.03

Therefore, the range of possible break-even stock prices for buying the calls would be between $206.20 and $208.03 (also sorted from lowest to highest).
